3:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"MEXC calculates AAVE/USDT funding rates every 8 hours at 00:00, 08:00, and 16:00 UTC using a premium index weighted against Binance, OKX, and Bybit spot prices. The funding fee is exchanged between long and short position holders based on the 8-hour TWAP of the premium. MEXC's zero maker fees on perpetual contracts make it particularly attractive for funding rate arbitrage strategies, though takers pay 0.03%."}]
4:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","AAVE","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"AAVE's status as a leading DeFi lending protocol creates significant funding rate volatility during governance events and protocol updates. The token's correlation with broader DeFi sentiment makes it prone to funding rate premiums during bull markets and discounts during bear cycles, creating consistent arbitrage opportunities."}]]}]
5:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"AAVE/USDT funding rates on MEXC typically range from -0.5% to +1.2% during normal market conditions, with extreme spikes reaching ±3% during major DeFi events. The pair shows strong correlation with ETH funding rates but often trades at a 20-40 basis point premium due to MEXC's retail-heavy user base. Funding rates tend to be most negative during AAVE governance proposal periods when institutional traders short against spot holdings for voting purposes. Weekend funding periods often show increased volatility as MEXC's Asian user base drives different flow patterns compared to Western-focused exchanges."}]]}]
6:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"The zero maker fee structure on MEXC creates asymmetric arbitrage opportunities where traders can capture funding payments while paying minimal trading costs for hedging. Cross-exchange arbitrage between MEXC and Binance/OKX often yields 50-150 basis points annually when accounting for the fee differential. AAVE's lending protocol utility creates natural hedging opportunities where users can earn lending yields while collecting negative funding rates. The 8-hour interval timing aligns poorly with other major exchanges, creating temporal arbitrage windows during rate convergence periods."}]]}]
7:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Considerations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"MEXC's thinner order books for AAVE/USDT can create significant slippage during volatile periods, potentially eroding arbitrage profits. The exchange's questionable volume reporting raises concerns about market manipulation affecting funding rate calculations. Regulatory uncertainty around MEXC's operations creates counterparty risk that traders must factor into longer-term funding rate strategies. AAVE's smart contract risks and potential governance changes can cause sudden spot-perp dislocations that overwhelm funding rate profits with mark-to-market losses."}]]}]
8:["$","$Ld",null,{"items":[{"question":"What makes MEXC's AAVE funding rates different from other exchanges?","answer":"MEXC offers zero maker fees on AAVE perpetuals and uses 8-hour funding intervals instead of the standard hourly rates. The exchange's retail-focused user base and aggressive listing strategy often creates different funding rate dynamics compared to institutional-heavy platforms like Binance or Deribit."},{"question":"How do AAVE governance events affect MEXC funding rates?","answer":"Major AAVE governance proposals typically drive funding rates negative as institutional holders short perpetuals to maintain delta neutrality while voting. MEXC's funding rates are often more extreme during these events due to lower liquidity and retail trader positioning."},{"question":"Is MEXC AAVE/USDT suitable for automated funding arbitrage?","answer":"The zero maker fees make it attractive for high-frequency strategies, but thin order books and potential connectivity issues require careful risk management. The 8-hour funding schedule is less suitable for automated strategies compared to hourly rates on other platforms."},{"question":"What are the main risks of funding arbitrage with MEXC AAVE positions?","answer":"Key risks include MEXC's regulatory uncertainty, thin liquidity causing slippage, potential manipulation affecting funding calculations, and AAVE's smart contract risks. The exchange's volume reporting accuracy also raises concerns about fair price discovery for funding rate calculations."}]}]
